{#-
  Reading-side document-reference (citation) protocol — for any agent receiving
  material that cites Document-Refs. Context variables (all optional):
    doc_ref_cvl        — cited work may reference cvl_researcher results, and the reader
                         has `cvl_document_ref` (default: true)
    doc_ref_code       — cited work may reference code_explorer results, and the reader
                         has `code_document_ref` (default: true)
    doc_ref_artifact   — the citing material, as a noun phrase (default: "CVL you review";
                         e.g. "feedback you receive" for authors reading judge feedback)
    doc_ref_scrutinize — include the judge-role tail ("the interpretation is yours to
                         scrutinize"); set false for non-judge readers (default: true)
-#}
{%- set _cvl = doc_ref_cvl | default(true) -%}
{%- set _code = doc_ref_code | default(true) -%}
{%- set _artifact = doc_ref_artifact | default("CVL you review") -%}
{%- set _scrutinize = doc_ref_scrutinize | default(true) -%}
{%- set tool_noun = "tools" if (_cvl and _code) else "tool" -%}
The {{ _artifact }} may reference {% if _cvl %}cvl research document {% endif %}{% if _cvl and _code %}or code explorer agent {% elif _code %}code explorer agent {% endif %}reference ids.
These document references are "citations" to results returned by the {% if _cvl %}cvl_researcher {% endif %}{% if _cvl and _code %}or {% endif %}{% if _code %}`code_explorer` {% endif %}{{ tool_noun }}.
You can use the {% if _cvl %}`cvl_document_ref` {% endif %}{% if _cvl and _code %}or {% endif %}{% if _code %}`code_document_ref` {% endif %}{{ tool_noun }} to retrieve these results
and review the evidence being cited in the {{ _artifact }}.

**IMPORTANT**: The results returned from a document reference were generated by exactly the same research {{ tool_noun }} you have access to.
Treat the results in these documents as established facts; do *not* reverify them by calling the relevant {{ tool_noun }} again.
{% if _scrutinize %}
However, the author's *interpretation* of those facts - the design/implementation decisions, the constructs chosen, the way the citations
are used to justify its choice -- is exactly what you are here to scrutinize.
A citation to a relevant research result does not by itself justify the work that cites it.
{% if _cvl -%}
For example, a CVL specification that uses explicit `forall` quantification in an invariant while citing a relevant CVL research result on the `forall`
syntax does *NOT* itself justify violating the CVL guideline against explicit forall quantification.
{%- endif %}
{% endif %}
